# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: derbyshire-children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital has its origins in the **Hospital for Sick Children** on St Michael's Hill founded in 1866.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The initial building was a large converted dwelling house on Royal Fort Road, south of the Royal Fort gatehouse, with accommodation for 40 patients.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the hospital's first salaried doctors was the pioneering female surgeon, Eliza Walker, appointed as House Surgeon in 1873.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] A much expanded hospital was built nearby to the designs of Robert Carwen in the Tudor gothic revival style in 1885.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Only the entrance building fronting on to St Michael's Hill now survives.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital was later renamed as the **Bristol Royal Hospital for Sick Children**.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The new Children's Hospital opened on 22 April 2001, replacing the old children's hospital on St Michael's Hill, at a cost £30 million.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the main aims of the design, in addition to providing the most up-to-date facilities possible, was to overcome many of the difficulties that face patients, families and staff.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In February 2014, it was agreed an inquiry would be held into the Bristol heart scandal, following heart surgery deaths at the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The inquiry published a report in June 2016, saying that “parents had been let down”.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] An extension was built to accommodate services moved from Frenchay Hospital in 2014, including neuroscience, scoliosis surgery, burns and plastic surgery, bringing all inpatient children's services in Bristol to one location.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2015, a neuro-rehabilitation unit was built to support the moved services.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In May 2014, a new helipad on the roof of the neighbouring Bristol Royal Infirmary became fully operational and will receive air ambulances from Bristol and the surrounding area, which will speed up transfer times for patients who are air lifted to the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The HELP Appeal supported the construction of the helipad with a grant of £500,000.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Wallace & Gromit's Grand Appeal is the only charity that fundraises exclusively for the hospital and the neonatal intensive care unit at St Michael's Hospital, to provide facilities and comforts for patients and their families.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal raised £12M towards the new building for the child-friendly hospital, which opened in April 2001.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Sculptures were decorated by a range of artists and celebrities, including Joanna Lumley, Sir Peter Blake, Cath Kidston and Jools Holland.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] At the end of the art trail, each sculpture was auctioned to raise funds for Bristol Children's Hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal has pledged to raise £3.5M for equipment for Bristol Children's Hospital, including a state of the art CT Scanner, an intraoperative MRI scanner, family facilities and child-friendly artwork to help save the lives of sick children at the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] All funds raised by Gromit Unleashed will contribute towards this.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Bristol & Weston Hospitals Charity (BWHC) raises around £2M for all ten hospitals in the trust.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It provides equipment, ward refurbishments and additional extras.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It was formerly known as Above & Beyond and has existed since 1974.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2013, the charity's Golden Gift Appeal raised £6M.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 1997, arts consultant, Lesley Greene, was commissioned to develop an arts strategy for the new hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] This project was committed to integrated designs, a commitment to consultation and the family.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Her active research programme led to the appointment of lead artist, Ray Smith, Eva Elsner, and Annie Lovejoy who contributed to the planning of the commissions programme.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Artworks were commissioned from more than twenty artists, many of which were site specific.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] These commissions were funded by the hospital's own fundraising arm, The Wallace and Gromit Grand Appeal.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Records of the Bristol Royal Hospital for Children are held at Bristol Archives (Ref.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] 37424) (online catalogue) and School of Nursing records (Ref.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] The **Children's Acute Transport Service** (CATS) is a publicly funded specialised regional intensive care transport service for critically ill children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is the busiest Paediatric Intensive Care Transport Service in the UK and covers the 50 District General Hospitals in the North Thames and East Anglia regions of England.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is part of the Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Only a proportion of hospitals have a Paediatric Intensive Care Unit PICU.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Therefore, most critically ill children initially present to hospitals without a PICU.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Paediatric Intensive Care Transport Services are designed to provide the safe and rapid transfer of these children to a regional PICU.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS was created in 2001 as a collaborative service for the North Thames Regional PICU's: The Royal Brompton Hospital, St Mary's Hospital, London and Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS receives ~2200 referral calls and performs ~1200 critical care retrievals each year.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Over 75% of these children are too unwell to breathe for themselves and require anaesthesia and a ventilator.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] A third need inotropic (inotrope) support, and about 5% require inhaled nitric oxide during transport.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Telephone advice, liaison with sub-specialist medical services and outreach education are also important parts of the service's activity.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Service Level Agreements (SLA) exist with Great Ormond Street Hospital and the Freeman Hospital in Newcastle for ECMO (extracorporeal membrane oxygenation) retrievals.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS also provide a paediatric intensive care transport service with Great Ormond Street Hospital for retrieval of children with Vein of Galen malformations requiring radiological ablation.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] 5-10% of retrievals are performed by air ambulance.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] This is via both helicopter and fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] For many of these urgent long distance transfers, the team works with the aircraft and the crews of HM Coastguard helicopters.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS have moved many paediatric patients internationally.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS has received accreditation from the Commission on Accreditation of Medical Transport Systems (CAMTS).
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] This independent, non-profit agency audits medical transport services against industry-established criteria.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS accreditation is for fixed-wing and rotary wing air medical transport services as well as ground inter-facility critical care services.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Department of Health, Health and Social Care Award, National Winners 2005.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] NHS intensive care consultants are responsible for service delivery, supervision of junior medical staff, provision of outreach education and service development.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] All full-time CATS consultant intensivists, cover sessions in PICU/anaesthesia to maintain competencies in their base speciality.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] A team of full-time CATS nurses is responsible for service delivery, co-ordination of the outreach education program, and in-house training.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] In addition, over 50 nurses rotate from each of the 3 PICUs to cover the rota.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] A team of administrators provide 24-hour cover for the Referral Hotline and co-ordinate incoming referrals, teleconferencing and communication with clinical team members.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] Road ambulance retrievals are provided by St John Ambulance using bespoke CATS designed intensive care ambulances.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is the subject of an eight-part (8 x 30 minute) series called Children's Emergency, produced by September Films for BBC One.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-acute-transport-service] It aired between 4 May and 23 June 2010.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] CHSW was founded by Jill and Eddie Farwell in 1991, after spending many years travelling to Helen & Douglas House in Oxford with their own two life-limited children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] Following a feasibility study, they raised funds and Little Bridge House at Fremington near Barnstaple in North Devon opened in 1995, and instantly provided support for up to 200 families in the South West with life limited children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] The second hospice, Charlton Farm at Wraxall, North Somerset near Bristol, opened its doors to the first families in April 2007.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] The third hospice, Little Harbour, opened at Porthpean, St Austell, Cornwall in 2011.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] It offers a more local service to families from Cornwall and Plymouth.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] Children's Hospice South West's £5 million Precious Lives Appeal was set up to fund the building of this third hospice.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] In the year ending March 2020, CHSW's income was £15.8 million, which included £2.6M of government contracts and grants.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospice-south-west] It spent £5.8M on raising funds and £9.3M on running the hospices.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] A **children's hospital** **(CH)** is a hospital that offers its services exclusively to infants, children, adolescents, and young adults from birth up to until age 18, and through age 21 and older in the United States.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In certain special cases, they may also treat adults.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The number of children's hospitals proliferated in the 20th century, as pediatric medical and surgical specialties separated from internal medicine and adult surgical specialties.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Children's hospitals are characterized by greater attention to the psychosocial support of children and their families.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Some children and young people have to spend relatively long periods in hospital, so having access to play and teaching staff can also be an important part of their care.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] With local partnerships, this can include trips to local botanical gardens, zoos, and public libraries for instance.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In addition to psychosocial support, children's hospitals have the added benefit of being staffed by professionals who are trained in treating children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] A medical doctor that undertakes vocational training in paediatrics must also be accepted for membership by a professional college before they can practice paediatrics.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] These include the Royal Australasian College of Physicians (RACP), Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health (RCPCH), and the American Board of Pediatrics.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In New Zealand, the RACP offers vocational training in paediatrics.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Once RACP training is completed the doctor is awarded the Fellowship of the RACP (FRACP) in paediatrics.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] While many normal hospitals can treat children adequately, pediatric specialists may be a better choice when it comes to treating rare afflictions that may prove fatal or severely detrimental to young children, in some cases before birth.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Also, many children's hospitals will continue to see children with rare illnesses into adulthood, allowing for a continuity of care.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Prior to 19th century hospital reforms, the well-being of the child was thought to be in the hands of the mother; therefore, there was little discussion of children's medicine, and as a result next to no widespread formal institutions which focused on healing children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Dispensaries and foundling hospitals were the earliest forms of what would later become children's hospitals.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Florence's Hospital of the Innocent (Ospedale degli Innocenti) was originally a charity based orphanage which opened in 1445; its aim was to nurse sick and abandoned infants back to health.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Foundling hospitals such as the Foundling Hospital founded by Thomas Coram in 1741 were created to receive abandoned infants, nurse them back to health, teach them a trade or skill, and integrate them back into society.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Dispensaries funded by donations also provided medicine and medical attention to those who could not afford private care.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The Scottish paediatrician George Armstrong, who established the first British dispensary, in 1769, was against in-patient care for sick children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Objections to admission were sometimes based on pragmatic reasons, e.g. reducing the threat of cross infection from children with diseases such as typhus, diphtheria and measles, that were a major cause of infant mortality.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The voluntary nature of hospitals meant that such outbreaks were very costly.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In the mid-19th century western world, middle-class women and physicians became increasingly concerned about the well-being of children in poor living conditions.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Although infant mortality had begun to decline, it still remained a prominent issue.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Social reformers blamed the emergence of the industrial society and poor parents for not properly caring for their children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] By the 1870s, the prevalent view among doctors and nurses was that children were better off by being removed to hospital, away from the often poor, unsanitary conditions at home.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In response, reformers and physicians founded children's hospitals.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] By the early 19th century, children's hospitals opened in major cities throughout Europe.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The first formally recognized paediatrics hospital was the Hôpital des Enfants Malades in Paris, which opened in 1802.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Great Ormond Street Hospital was established in London in 1852, and was the first British children's hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The Children's Hospital of Philadelphia in Pennsylvania was created in 1855.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The Royal Hospital for Sick Children, Edinburgh was the first children's hospital in Scotland and opened in 1860.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto, Ontario was the first Canadian children's hospital and opened in 1875.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] By the end of the 19th century, and the during the first two decades of the 20th century, the number of children's hospitals tripled in both Canada and the United States.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] From the 1850s to around 1910, most cities in the UK had built children's hospitals, which included a large number of prestigious hospitals such as the Royal Hospital for Sick Children, Glasgow, Great Ormond Street Hospital and the Royal Manchester Children's Hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Early western children's hospitals were independent institutions funded by voluntary donations, and from research.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Often, children could only be admitted if they were sponsored by a letter of recommendation from a hospital affiliate.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The "undeserving poor" were sent to workhouse infirmaries, whilst middle class children were generally cared for, and indeed operated on, at home.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Hospitals set their own rules and had their own way of working, including regulating admissions.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] They often excluded children under the age of two on humanitarian and pragmatic grounds and were often hesitant to admit children who required long-term care in fear that those lives would be lost or that long-term care would block beds for those in immediate need.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Early children's hospitals focused more on short-term care and treating mild illnesses rather than long-term intensive care.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Treating serious diseases and illnesses in early children's hospitals could result in the disease spreading throughout the hospital which would drain already limited resources.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] A serious disease outbreak in a children's hospital would result in more deaths than lives saved and would therefore reinforce the previous notion that people often died while in the hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In the 19th century, there was a societal shift in how children were viewed.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] This shift took away some of the parents' control and placed it in the hands of medical professionals.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] By the early 20th century, a child's health became increasingly tied to physicians and hospitals.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] This was a result of licensing acts, the formation of medical associations, and new fields of medicine being introduced across countries.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Voluntary or religiously associated female care was often replaced by care provided by professionally trained nurses.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Historically, many children's hospitals limited the ability of children and parents to interact, such as by limiting visiting hours.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] This approach was criticised for decades before shifts in practice occurred.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Nicholl argued that "separation from mother is often harmful".
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] During the interwar period, leading up to World War II, psychiatrists expressed concerns about children being away from parents, such as during hospitalisation.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Harry Edelston, a Psychiatrist in Leeds, detailed that children were emotionally damaged by their stay in hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In the post-war era, critiques became more widespread and studies were conducted to examine potential harms.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] René Spitz, an Austrian-American psychoanalyst, published an article in 1945 in which he noted deleterious effects of hospitalisation, based on his research with institutionalised children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Perry wrote a 1947 Lancet article that protested the restrictions of parental visits on hospitalized children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] However, Edelston wrote in 1948, that many of this colleagues still refused to believe in hospitalisation trauma Bowlby studied 44 juvenile thieves and found that a significantly high number had experienced early and traumatic separation from their mother.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In 1949, he used the data to write a report for the World Health Organization's on the mental health of homeless children in post-war Europe.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] With the introduction of penicillin into the majority of the medical community by the 1940s, the major objection by doctors and nurses, that visits by parents into hospital wards introduced cross infections had been removed.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] A major review in 1949, over an 11-month period, showed that children admitted to 26 wards in 14 hospitals showed no correlation between visits and cross infection from parents to children.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] By that time, the working practices of doctors and nurses, still posed the main objection to visiting.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] By the 1950s, British politicians were concerned enough about the impact of children's hospital policy to create a committee to research the welfare of sick children in hospital.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] This committee produced the Platt Report of 1959, recommending that children should have more access to their parents while ill.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The Report had effects on hospital care of children in the UK and New Zealand, Australia, Canada and the United States.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Using hospital discharge data from 2003 to 2011, the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) studied trends in aggregate hospital costs, average hospital costs, and hospital utilization.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The Agency found that for children aged 0–17, aggregate costs rose rapidly for the surgical hospitalizations and decreased for injury hospitalizations.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Further, average hospital costs, or cost per discharge, increased at least 2% for all hospitalizations and were expected to grow by at least 4% through 2013.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The exception to this was mental health hospitalizations, which saw a lower percentage increase of 1.2%, and was projected to increase only 0.9% through 2013.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Despite the rising aggregate costs and costs per discharge, hospitalizations (except for mental health hospitalizations) for children aged 0–17 decreased over the same time, and were projected to continue decreasing.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In 2006–2011, the rate of emergency department (ED) use in the United States was highest for patients aged under one year, but lowest for patients aged 1–17 years.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The rate of ED use for patients aged under one year declined over the same time period; this was the only age group to see a decline.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] Between 2008 and 2012, growth in mean hospital costs per stay in the United States was highest for patients aged 17 and younger.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In 2012 there were nearly 5.9 million hospital stays for children in the United States, of which 3.9 million were neonatal stays and 104,700 were maternal stays for pregnant teens.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] News & World Report* ranks the top children's hospitals and pediatric specialties in the United States.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] For the year 2010–2011, eight hospitals ranked in all 10 pediatric specialties.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] News & World Report* depends on a variety of factors.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] In past years (2007 was the 18th year of Pediatric Ranking), ranking of hospitals has been done solely on the basis of reputation, gauged by random sampling and surveying of pediatricians and pediatric specialists throughout the country.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/children-s-hospital] The ranking system used is currently under review.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The hospice helps seriously and terminally ill children and young adults from 0–23 years by providing specialist nursing care and emotional support.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] It has provided care for children and young people across Merseyside, Cheshire and North Wales since it opened in 1998.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The organisation has two sites: a hospice in Bebington, the Wirral, and the Hub in West Derby, Liverpool, that offers day care.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Support can be provided at Claire House or at home and can be for the child, young person or for family members.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The charity has featured on Children in Need in 2011, 2014 and 2016.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] It also has high-profile supporters including Steven Gerrard and Wayne Rooney.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] As of 2017, the charity is providing care for over 200 babies, children and young people and supporting more than 200 bereaved families.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] In July 2015 Claire House was rated as 'Outstanding' by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Claire House, Wirral is open 24 hours a day, seven days a week and offers a range of services.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Children can have fun in the multi-sensory room, art room, hydrotherapy pool and Jacuzzi.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] There is a separate wing complete with bar, sound system and Xbox for teenagers and young adults.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Claire House also provides end of life care, ensuring that a child's last days are as comfortable and memorable as possible.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] In 2016 the charity occupied a site in West Derby, Liverpool, that used to be a Carmelite Monastery.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The Claire House Liverpool Hub opened in the summer of 2017, offering services such as counselling, holistic therapies and hospice to home support.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Claire House hopes to one day open a new-state-of-the-art hospice on the site and reach out to more children in Merseyside.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Supporters of the charity include the Mowgli Trust which has donated £325,000.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The trust was established by Nisha Katona, whose company Mowgli Street Food is headquartered in Liverpool.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/derbyshire-children-s-hospital] The hospital was established as the Derbyshire Hospital for Sick Children in a Victorian building on North Street in 1877.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/derbyshire-children-s-hospital] Picture tiles depicting fairy tales and friezes of birds and animals which decorated the wards were removed during renovations in 1980, restored and re-installed in the mid-1980s.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/derbyshire-children-s-hospital] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948 and moved to a modern building on the Royal Derby Hospital site in 1996.
[src:derbyshire-children-s-hospital/derbyshire-children-s-hospital] It was the only entirely new children's hospital built in the UK in the twentieth century.
